'''Lead picrate''', Pb(C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>2</sub>(NO<sub>2</sub>)<sub>3</sub>O)<sub>2</sub>, is an organic chemical compound from the group of [[picrate]]s, salt of [[picric acid]] and [[lead]] with a +2 [[oxidation state]]. It is an initiating explosive, and thus highly sensitive.<ref>{{cite book | title = High Energy Materials: Propellants, Explosives and Pyrotechnics | author = Jai Prakash Agrawal | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | date = 2015}}</ref>
For demonstration purposes, it can be most easily and safely prepared ''in situ''. [[Picric acid]] is mixed with [[red lead]] (Pb<sub>3</sub>O<sub>4</sub>), and then heated. It is not recommended that more than 50&nbsp;mg is ever made at any one time. At around 130–160&nbsp;°C, as the picric acid melts, the mixture detonates violently.
